<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>TF-1 Right Triangle Trigonometry</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      This outcome covers using right triangles to solve problems involving trigonometric 
      ratios. You should be able to use the definitions of the six trigonometric functions to 
      find missing sides and angles in right triangles. You should also be able to apply these 
      skills to solve trigonometric functions of any point in the coordinate plane.
      
    </p>
    <p>For the quiz on this outcome you would be given 30 minutes to complete 2 problems. Here are samples 
      of the types of problems you will encounter:</p>
  </introduction>
  <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Simplifying Expressions: Simplify algebraic expressions by combining like terms and applying the 
        distributive property. Answers should be completely simplified.</p></li>
        <li><p>Basics of Graphing: Give a graph with appropriate scales and labels. The line should have the 
          correct intercepts and general behavior.</p></li>
      <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
        that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
      <li><p>Mathematical Communication: Solutions should be presented in a clear and logical manner, with 
        appropriate use of mathematical notation and terminology. Equations should have at most one equal 
        sign and expressions on both sides.</p></li>
      <li><p>Solve a right triangle: Given two sides of a right triangle, find the missing side and use the 
        trigonometric definitions to find the values of the six trigonometric functions.</p></li>
      <li><p>Find the trigonometric functions of a point: Given a point in the coordinate plane, draw the 
        angle in standard position; draw and label the reference triangle. Find the values of the 
        six trigonometric functions using the definitions of the trigonometric functions and the signs 
        based on the quadrants in the coordinate plane.</p></li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

  
  <page>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>
           Given a right triangle RST with legs s=9 and t=12:
      </p></introduction>
      <task>
          <statement><p>Find the values of the six trigonometric functions of angle T.</p></statement>
          <hint><p>Find the value of r then use the definitions of the trigonometric functions to find the values.</p></hint>
          <answer><p><m>sin T = \frac{12}{15}</m>, <m>\cos T = \frac{9}{15}</m>, 
            <m>\tan T = \frac{12}{9}</m>, <m>\csc T = \frac{15}{12}</m>, 
            <m>\sec T = \frac{15}{9}</m>, <m>\cot T = \frac{9}{12}</m></p></answer>
          <solution><p>First, we find the value of r using the Pythagorean theorem: 
            <m>r = \sqrt{s^2 + t^2}</m>
            <m>r = \sqrt{9^2 + 12^2}</m>
            <m>r= \sqrt{81 + 144} </m>
            <m>r= \sqrt{225} = 15</m></p>
            <p>Now we can use the definitions of the trigonometric functions:</p>
            <p><m>\sin T = \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{hypotenuse}} = \frac{12}{15}</m></p>
            <p><m>\cos T = \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}} = \frac{9}{15}</m></p>
            <p><m>\tan T = \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{adjacent}} = \frac{12}{9}</m></p>
            <p><m>\csc T = \frac{\text{hypotenuse}}{\text{opposite}} = \frac{15}{12}</m></p>
            <p><m>\sec T = \frac{\text{hypotenuse}}{\text{adjacent}} = \frac{15}{9}</m></p>
            <p><m>\cot T = \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{opposite}} = \frac{9}{12}</m></p>
        </solution>
      </task>    
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>Given a right triangle UVW with leg u=8 and hypotenuse v=17:</p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find the values of the six trigonometric functions of angle U.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Find the value of w then use the definitions of the trigonometric functions to find the values.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\sin U = \frac{15}{17}</m>, <m>\cos U = \frac{8}{17}</m>, 
          <m>\tan U = \frac{15}{8}</m>, <m>\csc U = \frac{17}{15}</m>, 
          <m>\sec U = \frac{17}{8}</m>, <m>\cot U = \frac{8}{15}</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>First, we find the value of w using the Pythagorean theorem: 
          <m>w = \sqrt{v^2 - u^2}</m>
          <m>w = \sqrt{17^2 - 8^2}</m>
          <m>w= \sqrt{289 - 64} </m>
          <m>w= \sqrt{225} = 15</m></p>
          <p>Now we can use the definitions of the trigonometric functions:</p>
          <p><m>\sin U = \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{hypotenuse}} = \frac{15}{17}</m></p>
          <p><m>\cos U = \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}} = \frac{8}{17}</m></p>
          <p><m>\tan U = \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{adjacent}} = \frac{15}{8}</m></p>
          <p><m>\csc U = \frac{\text{hypotenuse}}{\text{opposite}} = \frac{17}{15}</m></p>
          <p><m>\sec U = \frac{\text{hypotenuse}}{\text{adjacent}} = \frac{17}{8}</m></p>
          <p><m>\cot U = \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{opposite}} = \frac{8}{15}</m></p>
      </solution>
      </task>    
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction><p>The point (-4,6) is on the terminal side of angle θ in 
        standard position:</p></introduction>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Sketch the angle θ in standard position. Sketch and label the
          reference triangle.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Use the given point to form a right triangle with the origin and 
          the x-axis. Use the Pythagorean theorem to find the hypotenuse.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><image width="60%">
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org"
                            label="prefigure-tf1a-sample">
                  <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                    <coordinates bbox="(-10,-10,10,10)">
                      <grid spacings="((-10,2,10),(-10,2,10))"/>
                      <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                      <line endpoints="((-4,6),(0,0))" stroke="blue" label-location="0.4"><m>2\sqrt{13}</m></line>
                      <line endpoints="((-4,0),(0,0))" stroke="blue" label-location="0.4"><m>-4</m></line>
                      <line endpoints="((-4,0),(-4,6))" stroke="blue" label-location="0.4"><m>6</m></line>
                      <rectangle lower-left="(-4,0)" dimensions="(0.2,0.2)" fill="blue"/>
                    </coordinates>
                <annotations>
                  <annotation ref="figure"
                    text="The graph of the function is a right triangle with vertices at the origin, (-4,0) and (-4,6). 
                    The hypotenuse has length 2\sqrt{13}, the adjacent leg has length -4 and the opposite leg has length 6.">
                        </annotation>
                </annotations>
              </diagram>
            </prefigure></image></p></answer>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement><p>Find the values of the six trigonometric functions of angle θ.</p></statement>
        <hint><p>Find the value of r then use the definitions of the trigonometric functions to find the values.</p></hint>
        <answer><p><m>\sin θ = \frac{6}{10}</m>, <m>\cos θ = \frac{-4}{10}</m>, 
          <m>\tan θ = \frac{6}{-4}</m>, <m>\csc θ = \frac{10}{6}</m>, 
          <m>\sec θ = \frac{10}{-4}</m>, <m>\cot θ = \frac{-4}{6}</m></p></answer>
        <solution><p>First, we find the value of r using the distance formula: 
          <m>r = \sqrt{(-4)^2 + 6^2}</m>
          <m>r = \sqrt{16 + 36}</m>
          <m>r= \sqrt{52} = 2\sqrt{13}</m></p>
          <p>Now we can use the definitions of the trigonometric functions:</p>
          <p><m>\sin θ = \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{hypotenuse}} = \frac{6}{2\sqrt{13}}</m></p>
          <p><m>\cos θ = \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{hypotenuse}} = \frac{-4}{2\sqrt{13}}</m></p>
          <p><m>\tan θ = \frac{\text{opposite}}{\text{adjacent}} = \frac{6}{-4}</m></p>
          <p><m>\csc θ = \frac{\text{hypotenuse}}{\text{opposite}} = \frac{2\sqrt{13}}{6}</m></p>
          <p><m>\sec θ = \frac{\text{hypotenuse}}{\text{adjacent}} = \frac{2\sqrt{13}}{-4}</m></p>
          <p><m>\cot θ = \frac{\text{adjacent}}{\text{opposite}} = \frac{-4}{6}</m></p>
      </solution>
      </task>    
      </exercise>
  </page>
</worksheet>